The billionaire technology entrepreneur’s company announced it is "pending service coverage or regulatory approval". Kenyans, however, can order and deposit an amount of Ksh12,260 ($99) which is fully refundable to get the service if approved. "Order now to reserve your Starlink. Starlink is targeting service in your area starting in Q2 2023. Availability is subject to regulatory approval. Within each coverage area, orders are fulfilled on a first-come, first-served basis," the company said on its website. The multinational said it is targeting Nairobi, Kisumu, Mombasa, and Nakuru, among other towns, in starting from the three months ending June. The company’s entry into Kenya will be faced with stiff competition from some players in the business. --TheEastAfrican--